post_text:
Just in case you missed it....

On August 17th from 11am- 1pm the school will be providing health physicals for middle school students for the upcoming school year. If your middle school child participated in athletics last year, we have an active physical on file and a new one is not required at this time. However, we will need updated valid insurance information.

Any students (including this years 6th graders) who did not participate in middle school athletics last year, and wishes to this year, will need a physical.

Please park at the top parking lot near the gym doors. Paperwork will be brought to you. Upon completion, the student will be brought in the school to receive their physical.

post_text:
Back to school update

Virtual instruction will be available. If you select virtual instruction, your child will be enrolled as a virtual student through October 22, 2020, at which time parents will meet with the virtual classroom team and determine if this continues to be the best educational setting for your child. Virtual instruction will require the student to log in to assignments and videos on a daily basis. Teachers will be making contact with all students multiple times during the week. Virtual instruction will have the same expectations as a seated class.

post_text:
Back to school information

The school is asking that if possible parents/guardians transport their children to and from school on a daily basis. For the safety of the students and bus drivers, students who ride the bus will be required to wear a face shield or mask while they are on the bus. They will need to have it on when they enter the bus and will wear it until they are in their classroom. If you need your child to ride the bus, you will need to complete the transportation release form at registration

post_text:
Some helpful hints/reminders from Mrs. Givens (part 2)

How to handle struggles with education at home:

Communicate with your student's teacher and/or counselor, depending on the concern. At SKS, your student's teacher can put you in contact with the counselor, if needed. They are there to help!
Take it easy on yourself. This is not a typical situation, and you are not expected to be perfect.
Be sure to take care of yourself. If you wear yourself out you cannot help your student. We are all in this together!

What if we run out of school work:

This is a great opportunity to teach kids "real life" skills! Teach them how to do laundry, cook a meal, or change a tire. You can also incorporate school subjects into these lessons. For example, you can teach math such as measuring or adding/subtracting to adjust the size of the recipe while you are cooking.
If you're still looking for more, there are online resources. Please, use your discretion in which sites are appropriate.
If all else fails, READ!!! Reading is the foundation of all learning and is always helpful to practice.

post_text:
Some helpful hints/reminders from Mrs. Givens (part 1)

How to talk with kids about what is going on:

It is important to be honest with kids while being sure to communicate with them at an age-appropriate level (not all ages are able to understand/deal with all the details of what is going on).
Allow them to tell you their feelings, and validate those feelings.
Discussing what you do and do not have control of, along with making a plan for what you can control (washing hands, staying home, etc.) can help empower kids and calm their nerves.

How to minimize the stresses that go with being home all day:

Keep routines, such as bathtime, getting up by a certain time, etc., keeping in mind some typical routines may need to be adjusted during social distancing.
Make plans for how you want days to go, communicate those plans with kids, and even include kids in making the plans to encourage buy-in from them.
Set boundaries and communicate expectations for the family.
Create personal spaces for members of the family to have time to themselves.

Did you know....when we all respond to the 2020 Census, our communities will get the money we need to improve roads, schools, hospitals, and more. Shell Knob is a Title 1 school and the Census determines our Title 1 funds. So filling out your Census is vital for our school.

We have to rally together and get the word out for the 2020 Census. The Census is live online, www.my2020cenus.gov or by phone 1.844.300.2020.

post_text: Shell Knob School District will be delivering meals by bus March 23rd through April 3, Monday-Friday. The once daily delivery will include breakfast, lunch, and a snack. We will deliver to everyone on the bus routes on Monday, March 23rd. At that time, parents can instruct the driver as to whether they would like the delivery continued or not. If your child is a preschool student or if they do not ride the bus, please call Dr Fransen at 417-858-6743 ext 235, and she will get your information. We will also provide meals for your High School student as well. Please bear with us, we are navigating new territory. Drivers will deliver between 10:30 and 12:30.

post_text:
Shell Knob middle school students 6th -8 th grade
entered a competition in the fall held by our local
VFW Post called the Patriot’s Pen. However, this is not just a local competition. This is a national essay
writing competition. The VFW is dedicated to
promoting future generations to love and learn about this great country. The top essays are sent by the local VFW Post to the district levels. If the essays are good enough they continue on. The hope is that they will go to the national level. The theme this year was “What Makes America Great”. The students plan, organize, write and edit their essays with no help beyond basic editing, so that
their writing will be an original work by them. The president of our Local VFW Post Dave
Atkinson with Dennis Page awarded the 1 st -3 rd place winners on January 24th. Students were awarded a certificate, medal, and money.

post_text:
Mystery Monday reveal is Mr. Mitch!

How long have you worked at SKS? A little over 13 years.

What is your favorite way to relax? Anything that involves nature

What did you want to be when you grew up? A fireman. My dad was a fireman until I was in the 3rd grade.

Where is the most exciting place you have ever visited? Hawaii, it is a magical place.

Please tell us something interesting or unique about yourself that we may not know: my grandparents retired and moved here in 1965. My best summertime memories are in Shell Knob. I moved to Shell Knob with my 12 year old son in 1989 and bought Don Glass Heating and Air at the Viola corner. Life happened and I ended up moving back to Wichita after 1 year. My 1st grandchild was born in 1998 and grandpa’s need to be at the lake. I moved here permanently in 1999. I ride a sit down hydrofoil water ski for fun!

post_text:
Mystery Monday reveal.... Mrs. Riepl!

How long have you worked at SKS? This is my 25th year at SKS as a teacher but I started helping at ballgames 27 years ago when Mr. Riepl started there.

What is your favorite way to relax? I love to read and ride in our boat

What did you want to be when you grew up! I have wanted to be a teacher for as long as I can remember. I also thought about being a nurse when I was really young.

Where is the most exciting place you have ever visited? For our 20th anniversary we went to the Chichen Itza Mayan Ruins.

Please tell us something interesting or unique about yourself that we may not know.
I own a 1968 Ford California Special. It was my daily driver for many years. I fell in love with that car at the Sea World Mustang show in 1985.
